The time has come to knock down our bedroom. The last room in the house where nothing has been done, just a bit of decoration.
Remove the awful electric fireplace and hearth. Box in the chimney, replace the damaged plaster and sand. Build a custom closet.
We always start with a quick sketch on paper...
The messy stage is over.
I've found several dead birds at the back of the flue; all dried up :(
Ready for the plasterer next week.
Happy with the small nook on the side.
Insert the new closet here (not like we've already started drawing it yet).
Oh, look at what we've found behind the radiator!
And we even thought to add a lovely little ventilation outlet to prevent the chimney from taking in humidity.
The chimney sweep took care of installing the cap and the overhang. It should be a bit safer for the crows nesting up there 🪺
The plasterer is finished. We're installing the floor tomorrow!
The underlayment in foam board is in place, I improvised a wood shavings extractor with a roll of toilet paper as an attachment for the vacuum.
Some of the boards are sorted and ready to lay. We're just taking a tea break.
Well, progress was slow today due to super delicate cuts around the door frames to achieve a smooth transition to the hallway (which is also being laid). @user45@twitter.com cursed me out.
Done, but on the knees. The icing on the cake: the impossible instructions for assembling the new bed. We'll sleep well tonight!
The flooring for the hallway and all the baseboards still need to be done. The interior designer is coming in a month, so until then, at home, it's all about finishing the plaster without a finish.
A short evening DIY session to remove the lower sections of the door frames with a tenon saw or handsaw where we want the floor to be perfectly aligned.
The underlayment in foam board for the hallway is also in place.
We finished the hallway floor yesterday! Then off at 5am this morning to pick up Item 1 at Heathrow, followed by a nap and the final stretch for the hallway; baseboards installed. We'll deal with caulking once the glue has set.
